If you're working with the 'color' aesthetic, there's a related set of functions:

scale_colour_viridis_c for continuous data
scale_colour_viridis_b for binned data
scale_colour_viridis_d for discrete data (i.e., categorical)

#datascience #datavisualization #rstats

This function also has several options for other perceptually uniform color palettes.

For example, the 'plasma' color palette:

#datascience #datavisualization #rstats https://t.co/bjCE4W6LEy

Keep in mind: 

'viridis', 'inferno', 'plasma', and 'magma' are all related.

They are all "perceptually uniform" color palettes, so they have a similar perceptual structure WRT lightness.

But they use different hues.

#datascience #datavisualization #rstats https://t.co/Ab3z0RWaky

What's great about this is that the color palettes make the chart more intuitive.

It's a small multiple design (which some of you know: I love), but the color palette choice makes it more intuitive to read.

#datascience #Datavisualization #rstats https://t.co/aIs2JzHB4Q

To apply these alternative palettes, just use the "option=" parameter.

There are several possible arguments, including 'viridis', 'inferno', 'plasma', and 'magma'

#datascience #datavisualization #rstats

There's actually a family of these functions:

scale_fill_viridis_c for continuous data
scale_fill_viridis_b for binned data
scale_fill_viridis_d for discrete data (i.e., categorical)

#datascience #datavisualization #rstats https://t.co/4wAnk3cqAY

In R/ggplot2, you can apply the viridis color scale with scale_fill_viridis_c()

#DataScience #Datavisualization #rstats https://t.co/9KsTsrKwgw
